			<BR>
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Em <SPAN CLASS="em">A utility without good documentation is of no utility at all.</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.Pp
			<DIV>
			So you've written a utility, library, or driver (or started writing one), and you want to document your work.
			<BR>
			How do you get from code to
			</DIV>
			.Xr <A CLASS="man external"
			HREF="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=man&amp;apropos=0&amp;sektion=0&amp;manpath=OpenBSD+Current&amp;arch=i386&amp;format=html">man</A> 1
			<DIV>
			output?
			</DIV>
			.Pp
			<DIV>
			This site is a resource for composing well-formed and maintainable UNIX manuals in
			</DIV>
			.Xr <A CLASS="man external"
			HREF="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=mdoc&amp;apropos=0&amp;sektion=0&amp;manpath=OpenBSD+Current&amp;arch=i386&amp;format=html">mdoc</A> 7 <SPAN CLASS="offs">,</SPAN>
			<DIV>
			a language designed specifically for UNIX manuals and available by default on most reasonable UNIX installations.
			</DIV>
			.\"
